The Nepalese death toll from the Himalayan earthquake topped 562 on Wednesday as  rescue workers hampered by monsoon rains, aftershocks and washed out roads reached  remote areas and found 31 more bodies.
Indian officials said over 196 died in Sunday's  quake.
In Bihar, India, officials also said the water levels of six rivers had reached dangerous  levels and was still rising.
Further, the river embankments have cracked, posing threat of  flood.
The U.S. offered $25,000 in aid to both Nepal and India.
Britain, U.N. agencies and Red  Cross sent medical teams to Nepal, and the government began distributing rice. 
